There are 6 variables in the data:

  • Id: A number assigned to each person. (will not be taken into account in the project)
  • Age: The numeric age.
  • FEV: Forced Expiratory Volume, aka the amount of air a person can exhale in the first second of a forceful breath.
  • Hgt: The height (in feet) of each person
  • Male: If a person is male (1) or female (0).
  • Smoke: Wether a person smokes or not.

Part1: Bayesian Prediction

In this part of the project, we will assume the FEV variable follows a normal distribution.

\[ Xâ£Î¼,Ïâ¼ Normal\left(Î¼,\frac{1}{Ï}\right) \]

We will also assume the conjugate prior distribution for the normal distribution

We will assume the conjugate prior distribution for the normal distribution, that is, a normal-gamma prior distribution:

\[ Î¼â£Ïâ¼Normal \left(m,\frac{1}{cÏ}\right) \]

\[ Ïâ¼Gamma \left( \frac{a}{2}, \frac{b}{2} \right) \]

Plots and Introduction

We will visualize the variable we will be trying to predict, FEV

##      mean        sd   min   max
## 1 2.63678 0.8670591 0.791 5.793

Bayesian Normal Model

We will initialize the prior model parameters.

We will use the following variables: \[m^* = cm\]

\[c^* = c + n\]

\[a^* = a + n\] \[b^* = b+(nâ1)s^2 + \frac{cn}{c+n}(m-\overline{x})^2\] But first, we assume non-informative priors

m=0; c=0.05; a=0.05; b=0.05

n <- length(FEV)
mean.fev <- mean(FEV) 
var.fev <- var(FEV)

m.star = (c*m+n*mean.fev)/(c+n)
c.star = c+n
a.star = a+n
b.star = b+(n-1)*var.fev+c*n*(m-mean.fev)^2/(c+n)

We will, perform some analysis and create a plot of the prior and posterior joint distribution parameters.

library(nclbayes)

plot.joint <- function(mu, tau){
  NGacontour(mu,tau,m,c,a,b)
  NGacontour(mu,tau,m.star, c.star, a.star, b.star, add=TRUE,col="red")
  legend("topleft",c("prior","posterior"),lty=c(1, 1),col=c("black","red"))
}

mu <- seq(1.5,3,len=1000)
tau <- seq(0.5,1.5,len=1000)
plot.joint(mu, tau)

We will use Monte Carlo sampling to estimate the joint distribution of the data:

In our case, the distribution of the Gaussian parameters is:

\[Î¼â£Ï,dataâ¼Normal\left(2.63, \frac{1}{654.01Ï} \right)\]

\[Ïâ£dataâ¼Gamma\left( \frac{654.01}{2}, \frac{490.99}{2} \right)\]

(These are just the formulas we introduced before, but with the variables updated to their corresponding values)

Using Monte Carlo sampling, we may obtain a sample of size (M = 15.000) from this joint distribution using:

plot.monte.carlo <- function(mu.post, tau.post, mu, tau){
  plot(mu.post, tau.post, col="darkgrey")
  NGacontour(mu, tau, m.star, c.star, a.star, b.star, col="red",add=T)
  
}

M <- 15000
tau.post <- rgamma(M,shape=a.star/2,rate=b.star/2)
mu.post <- rnorm(M,mean=m.star,sd=sqrt(1/(c.star*tau.post)))
plot.monte.carlo(mu.post, tau.post, mu, tau)

The Credible Intervals for \(Î¼\) and \(Ï\) can be calculated like so:

# credible interval for mu
quantile(mu.post,c(0.025,0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 2.570101 2.702552
# credible interval for tau
quantile(tau.post,c(0.025,0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 1.195381 1.482479

Now, the Predictive Probabilities of the sample will be calculated.

The predictive density can be obtained by using the following formula:

\[f(xn+1â£data)=â«f(xâ£Î¼,Ï)f(Î¼,Ïâ£data)dÎ¼dÏ\]

If we assume a normal-gamma prior for \((Î¼,Ï)\), we obtain the predictive distribution for FEV

hist(FEV, freq=F)
x.axis <- seq(0, 7, by=0.01)
pred.mean <- m.star
scale=(c.star+1)*b.star/(c.star*a.star)
lines(x.axis,dt(x.axis-pred.mean/sqrt(scale), a.star)/sqrt(scale))

This is the comparison of the empirical cdf with the predictive cdf. We can see that we get a decent result, although not ideal.

plot(ecdf(FEV))
lines(x.axis, pt(x.axis - pred.mean / sqrt(scale), a.star))

The predictive probability that the value of FEV is 2.4 is:

val.to.estimate <- 2.4
1-pt((val.to.estimate - pred.mean)/sqrt(scale),a.star)
## [1] 0.6074349

Part2: Generalized Linear Models

Here, we will try to predict whether a person Smokes or not. We will be working with the same data as before.

The first step is to visualize the data.

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
boxplot(FEV ~ Smoke)
boxplot(Age ~ Smoke)
boxplot(Hgt ~ Smoke)
boxplot(Male ~ Smoke)

We will look at the plots among the variables, to see how they interact with each other. And try to see linearity among the variables.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(Age, FEV)
plot(Hgt, FEV)

We can see that there seems to be positive linear correlation among these variables. This might indicate the the higher the Age, the higher the Volume in the lungs. The same applies for Height; someone who is bigger in size will for sure be able to exhale more oxygen than a smaller person. (This will be taken into account later)

Classic Logistic Regression

The idea is to predict Smoke with the rest of the components of the data.

classic <- glm(Smoke ~ FEV + Age + Hgt + Male, family = binomial)

We will create a data.frame to store the probabilities. The rows will have different values from the min to the max of the values of each category. (This is just an approximation and is not a greedy search algorithm that finds the best values). It is rather a mere way to visualize the probability that our model has certain values for all the parameters.

predict.df <- data.frame(FEV = seq(0.5, 6, length.out = 40) , Age = seq(3, 19, length.out = 40),
                         Hgt = seq(46, 75, length.out = 40), Male = sample(0:1, 40, replace = TRUE))
predict.df['pred'] <- NA

Now its tike to look at the autocorrelation plots.

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))

acf(out[,1]) # intercept
acf(out[,2]) # FEV
acf(out[,3]) # Age
acf(out[,4]) # Hgt
acf(out[,5]) # Male

As we can see, they present clear autocorrelation, which can be dealt with using the MCMC package.

new.model <- MCMClogit(Smoke ~ FEV + Age + Hgt + Male, burnin=3000, mcmc=45000, thin=30, data=data)
plot(new.model)

# once we have a good mixin, we can take a look at the autocorrelations. 

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
acf(new.model[, 1])
acf(new.model[, 2])
acf(new.model[, 3])
acf(new.model[, 4])
acf(new.model[, 5])

It is clear to see that the is no more autocorrelation. Lastly, the posterior distribution of the failure probability will be obtained. We will use the best results we obtained here.

library(boot)
fail.prob <- inv.logit(out[,1] + 5.72*out[,2] + 18.2*out[,3] + 73.5*out[,4] + 0*out[,5])

plot(fail.prob)
